e. It was designed by the British Interplanetary Society. Liberty is the first small nuclear launch vehicle. The only other type is Orion. Ofcourse there are going to be developmental challenges but thats no reason not to post the story describing the concept. Anthony Tate of the Pro-Nuclear Space Society has a better concept than the BIS in my opinion. The story really is very good. Hopefully, it will get people asking questions and contributing ideas to solve problems.    <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Liberty Ship's Creator</span><br>  Posts: 223<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/9/03 1:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm28.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Article First Draft: Opening the Next Frontier</span><hr size=1> Wayne, I don't know Stan's E-mail addy, is it somewhere handy?  Failing that, I will write a response here and you can send it to him.  That way it comes from a familiar name and we have a simple contact path.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
So, to answer his concerns:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I have very very serious doubts.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
LOL!  So did I.  Heck, if it was easy, EVERYBODY would be doing it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Each of the seven reactors is operating at 80,000 megawatts. The Phoebus 2B operated at 4000 MW. There is a huge radiation level (neutrons and gamma rays)around one of the engines, no less seven of them. Bringing all up to power and temperature at once is not <br>
a simple task and the neutrons produced by each also effect all the others. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
He is correct, and I have not addressed the possibility of &quot;fratricide&quot; between the thrusters during startup.  Once the vortices are established, from the limited information I have been able to find on the web, the vorticity energy is easily capable of maintaining the fissile mass integrity.  It is possible that the launch structure will have to include single use shielding between the thrusters, to be replaced after each flight.  A couple of feet of iron should be adequate to isolate the cores, although I will freely acknowledge I have run no numbers on that yet.  <br>
<br>
Another area of concern is the fact that during gas core tests back in the late 60's and early 70's the energy output of the test core varied in a steady cyclic rhythm.  This was easy to control even with the tech of the time, but with seven cores, it would be advantageous to have them pulsing &quot;out of time&quot; with each other.  That way the neutron output of each core would peak at a different time from the others. Tests and modeling would have to be run on the entire array of engines running together to be sure this could be accomplished safely.  Luckily, the inherent dynamic stability of a gas core makes truly catastrophic transients nearly impossible.  I think.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
So little time, so much to do....  &lt;sigh&gt;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Any idea of the total inventory of Enriched uranium? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Using 37 trillion joules per pound as the energy content of U235/233 I have estimated it takes the complete burnup of less than 10 pounds of U235/233 to reach orbit.  Assuming burnup of only ten percent would be a total inventory of 100 pounds.  I would lean towards U233 bred from Th232, deliberately poisoned with U234 and U232 to reduce proliferation concerns.  Yes, it makes the fuel harder to handle, but I am perfectly willing to treat the stuff with kid gloves.  To be blunt, compared to the small lake of LH2 this thing would use, handling the fissile mass is not that much of an additional burden even if thoroughly poisoned.<br>
<br>
This mass could be cut to whatever enrichment percentage makes sense with U238.  This would be determined by testing and modeling of the cores with WAY more computing power than I can get my hands on.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Huge amount and huge safety criticality problem. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is correct, but handling the fuel mass as UF6 gas means advantageous geometry is easy to assure.  Simply use small diameter aluminum pipe for all the storage, with boron or cadmium incorporated right into the tube walls.  Never, ever, ever use a poor geometry vessel, and we should be fine.   We have literal decades of experience handling UF6 and to my knowledge have had a single criticality accident with it due to accumulation in a vacuum pump oil sump.  IE, UF6 is pretty thoroughly understood and can be handled with a degree of confidence, IF we are sure to maintain favorable geometry.<br>
<br>
Here's a thorough look at criticality accidents:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.csirc.net/10_Library/00_Reports/13638/la-13638.pdf">www.csirc.net/10_Library/...-13638.pdf</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Where does the electricity come from to heat the UF6? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Redundant array of fuel cells mounted above the main fuel tank, out of the neutron flux.  These would probably be the exact same ones as used on the Space Shuttle, I see no reason to waste money making a new design.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> There is a huge radiation shielding problem especially when on or near the ground and in the atmosphere from air scattered radiation reaching the crew and secondary gamma rays produced in the air from neutrons leaving the system.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is correct!  Note that the fissile mass is kept in a deeply non-critical state until launch, as it is stored in the narrow tubes of the fuel vaults.  Once the cores are lit, a very heavy neutron flux will escape.  The main neutron shield is the actual liquid hydrogen in the main fuel tank.  I have calculated the MFP in both gaseous and liquid hydrogen, and am confident that the many meters of liquid and gaseous hydrogen available during both launch and descent are a very capable shield against the vast majority of the neutrons.  Gamma emission in the fuel tank is controlled by using borated anti-slosh baffles.  Strategically placed slabs of borated polyethylene can be emplaced around the crew couches to handle any residual neutron flux.<br>
<br>
Recent breakthroughs in polymer radiation shields are very effective against even gamma rays, and given the mass we can apply to this problem, many centimeters of polymer can be incorporated into crew couches to reach safety levels we would be comfortable with.  This would specifically address gamma emitted by neutron capture in air in the first minutes of flight.<br>
<br>
Here is a link to a commercial company selling anti-radiation clothing.  Very neat stuff!   <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.radshield.com">www.radshield.com</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Here is a link to a recent study of gamma shielding effectiveness.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.radshield.com/RST_Livermore_Results.pdf">www.radshield.com/RST_Liv...esults.pdf</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Even Mev class gammas can be attenuated by two orders of magnitude for probably less than five tons per crew couch.  That much shielding would stop every thing else dead in its tracks.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   If the crew has ten people in it, we might have to dedicate 100,000 pounds to gamma shielding.  This is not a huge problem.<br>
<br>
Remember, we have the heavy lift capacity with this design to throw TONS of shielding around the crew if we decide we have to.  A meter of Demron would stop about anything short of a cosmic ray.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Twice the diamaeter of a Saturn 5 means the frontal cross section is huge (4x) along with drag. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Since we have such a large reserve of DeltaV and a high launch thrust, a flight profile for the admittedly tubby Liberty Ship would probably look quite a bit different than one for the SaturnV.  IE, go higher sooner, accepting more gravitation losses to lower drag losses.  There is an optimum point for trajectories that I will happily leave to the experts to determine.  As for MaxQ concerns, we have the ability to make the ship's structure over-built by a MUCH larger factor than we can with a chemically fueled launcher.   <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> The effects of radiation on componenets seems to be ignored <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
All structural components are made of low activation materials such as aluminum or silica.  Two hours after even such high exposures as the LibertyShip entails, these materials are non-radioactive as the most common isotopes created have short half-lives and benign decay chains.  Al28 and Al29 decay to stable silica, for example.  For more info see:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www2.bnl.gov/ton/">www2.bnl.gov/ton/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Control mechanisms can be made of low activation materials, or if delicate components such as computer modules must be placed close to the cores, they can be rad hardened with whatever levels of shielding are needed.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> The cores will be radioactive for a long time which matters if the system would be used for landing. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The fissile material is disposed of less than an hour into the flight, due to the gaseous nature of the fuel.  The structure of the engine is all low activation materials.  The fuel mass used for landing can be stored in the fuel vaults onboard the Liberty Ship and temporary shielding installed, or warmed and pumped into shielded ground storage on the tender ship.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> There is mention of high speed vacuum removal , .. from whence cometh the power.? creating a vacuum on the ground in the atmosphere is not <br>
easy....... <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
The portion of the fuel vault used for vacuum scram is pumped down by conventional cold-trap vacuum pumps through vacuum lines on the ground tender shortly before launch.  It only needs to hold vacuum for ten minutes, I think this is an achieveable goal.  Once in orbit, vacuum is easy to come by.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Also, vacuum in this application is relative:  The pressure in the core is tentatively set at 3000 psi, opening a valve into atmospheric pressure would probably work just fine.  The important thing is to expand and cool the UF6 fast enough, which is why a spray of liquid hydrogen would be used to remove heat from the fissile mass as quickly as if feasible.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> In short, I think this is a dream world . <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It may very well be!  But oh, what a dream to strive for.  Even if we only get halfway there, imagine what we would have made.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
