<br>
He has a good point and its one I've wrestled over in my mind but think is flawed. Sent him this reply.<br>
<br>
Hi Rob,<br>
<br>
&quot;Nuclear launch vehicles are technically feasible but politically unfeasible. I think it is better to avoid the subject, as it is not going to happen and will only supply ammo for anti-nuclear activists.&quot;<br>
Robert <br>
<br>
I respectfully disagree Rob. The public is fickle minded. Individuals are open to new ideas now more than ever in our history. <br>
<br>
There was a time once when we were all about exploration, conquest and colonization - we can now be defined as a civilization that focuses on internal problems that will or can never be completely solved. <br>
<br>
A cold shudder or chill goes up my spine looking at old black and white photographs of people, events, machines, inventions, proposals and visionary schemes from the early part of the last century. <br>
<br>
To see what could have and should have been is sobering to say the least. That generation of yesteryear believed so firmly in science, technology and the progress of Western Man in all areas of life, that it is easy to see why they have been called 'The Greatest Generation'. They believed that science (understanding) and technology (application) would lead to a higher standard of living, which it did. They believed in letting technology solve its own problems. They believed in grand projects of engineering.<br>
<br>
I believe we are coming full circle to a new age of exploration and discovery. The luddites peaked during the 60's. They were ignored during Cassini. Columbia gave them no ammunition. Their mantra has worn very thin. I recall how Orion was explained to a captivated audience onboard an airflight during the 60's. One of the interesting tales told in George Dyson's book. The overwhelming majority were in favour of more research. Before we decide on the political feasibility of nuclear launchers we should first make the public aware that the concept exists. The publics opinion on the matter might surprise a lot of leaders. From what I have observed, most people who are aware of the nuclear initiative already think it is a first stage rocket. Do you see marches in the streets? Ignorance is what holds us back and empowers those against progress. Thats why I started the movement. A more informed public can make up its own mind on balance. We live in a World of Star Trek fans and other dreamers who are just beginning to realise that fusion, anti-matter and hyperdrives are many decades away if ever possible. Let the luddite minority scream about this research. It is only missions that count and Nasa is not planning on launching any first stage nuclear vehicles soon.<br>
<br>
Trust me. If a nuclear vehicle that promises airline like access to space can be shown to be acceptably safe, the public will come on side. They should atleast be given an opportunity to decide for themselves. I believe most would welcome the challenge of opening up a new frontier. Public opinions change from one generation to the next but that change is always guided. We shouldn't leave them in the dark or treat them as children. By the very act we are ensuring they do remain like children in regards to this issue. Evolution was heavily contested but the truth always wins out in the end. <br>
<br>
